<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In Central Asia, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. philadelphica" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="philadelphica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. philadelphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been commonly confused with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. angulata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from the latter by ovate-lanceolate leaves on shorter petioles (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F7453067" captionText="Figure 20. Physalis philadelphica in Bishkek (single plant) (photo by G. Lazkov, 15 August 2015)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80804.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/587108" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">20</figureCitation>
), intensely yellow corollae with prominent dark brown spots at the base (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="F7453071" captionText="Figure 21. Physalis philadelphica in Bishkek (small-sized flower) (photo by G. Lazkov, 15 August 2015)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80804.figure21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/587109" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">21</figureCitation>
), shorter pedicels, and fruiting calyces indistinctly (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="F7453075" captionText="Figure 22. Physalis philadelphica in Bishkek (immature fruits) (photo by G. Lazkov, 15 August 2015)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80804.figure22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/587110" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">22</figureCitation>
) angled in fruit (
<bibRefCitation author="Terrones, Alejandro" journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Fennica" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7453021" refString="Terrones, Alejandro, Moreno, Joaquin, Juan, Ana, 2020. Barcoding eases the taxonomic identification of alien plants: the case of the genus Physalis (Solanaceae) in the Iberian Peninsula (Spain). In: Annali di Botanica." title="Barcoding eases the taxonomic identification of alien plants: the case of the genus Physalis (Solanaceae) in the Iberian Peninsula (Spain)" volumeTitle="Annali di Botanica." year="2020">Terrones et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Distribution</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="native distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Native distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Native to Central America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="secondary distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Secondary distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
Widely cultivated as a fruit crop. Introduced in many countries of North America, Europe, Africa, Asia, Australia. Archaeophyte in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Gonzalez-Perez, Julio Emmanuel" journalOrPublisher="Scientia Horticulturae" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7454317" refString="Gonzalez-Perez, Julio Emmanuel, Guerrero-Beltran, Jose Angel, 2021. Tomatillo or husk tomato (Physalis philadelphica and Physalis ixocarpa): A review. Scientia Horticulturae 288" title="Tomatillo or husk tomato (Physalis philadelphica and Physalis ixocarpa): A review" volume="288" year="2021">
<normalizedToken originalValue="González-Pérez">Gonzalez-Perez</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Guerrero-Beltrán">Guerrero-Beltran</normalizedToken>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
), neophyte elsewhere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In arid areas of Asia, the species was introduced to Turkey in the 1990s as a weed of irrigated cotton fields (
<bibRefCitation author="Buekuen, B." journalOrPublisher="Turkish Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="405 - 407" refId="B7454234" refString="Buekuen, B., Uygur, F. N., Uygur, S., Tuerkmen, N., Duesenli, A., 2002. A new record for the flora of Turkey: Physalis philadelphica Lam. var. immaculata Waterf. (Solanaceae). Turkish Journal of Botany 26: 405 - 407" title="A new record for the flora of Turkey: Physalis philadelphica Lam. var. immaculata Waterf. (Solanaceae)" volume="26" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bükün">Buekuen</normalizedToken>
et al. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
), where it became invasive and quickly gained the top status among other weeds (
<bibRefCitation author="Buekuen, B." journalOrPublisher="Weed Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="404 - 412" refId="B7454244" refString="Buekuen, B., 2004. Critical periods for weed control in cotton in Turkey. Weed Research 44 (5): 404 - 412" title="Critical periods for weed control in cotton in Turkey" volume="44" year="2004">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bükün">Buekuen</normalizedToken>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
). In other arid territories, this species is not invasive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="distribution in central asia">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Distribution in Central Asia</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Reported from Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan for the first time here.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In Kazakhstan, the species was observed for the first (and only) time in 2019, in a damp place at 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jabağyly">Jabagyly</normalizedToken>
Village, Turkestan Region (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkamaitė, R." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Life Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7453095" refString="Plantarium Plants and lichens of Russia and neighboring countries: open online galleries and plant identification guide https://www.plantarium.ru/lang/en.html 2021-07-12T00:00:00+03:00" year="2015">Plantarium 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">In Kyrgyzstan, it was found for the first time in Bishkek, in 2015.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In Uzbekistan, the species was originally recorded in 1929 and 1930 as a weed of cotton cultivation (
<bibRefCitation author="Kovalevskaya, S. S." journalOrPublisher="Flora of Uzbekistan" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7454266" refString="Kovalevskaya, S. S., 1961. . Flora of Uzbekistan Vol. 5" volume="Vol. 5" year="1961">Kovalevskaya 1961</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Khassanov, F. O." journalOrPublisher="Flora of Uzbekistan" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7454253" refString="Khassanov, F. O., Sennikov, A. N., Juramurodov, I. J., 2020. . Flora of Uzbekistan Vol. 3" volume="Vol. 3" year="2020">Khassanov et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), but this record was erroneously based on misidentified specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. angulata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see discussion under that species). Since 2008, the species was repeatedly collected as a ruderal plant in Tashkent (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkamaitė, R." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Life Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7453095" refString="Plantarium Plants and lichens of Russia and neighboring countries: open online galleries and plant identification guide https://www.plantarium.ru/lang/en.html 2021-07-12T00:00:00+03:00" year="2015">Plantarium 2021</bibRefCitation>
). Besides, recently it was noted (albeit with a low abundance) as a weed in Tashkent Region: on late carrot fields in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Oqqoʻrgʻon">Oqqoʻrgʻon</normalizedToken>
District (
<bibRefCitation author="Axmedov, X. A." journalOrPublisher="Internauka" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="26 - 27" refId="B7454288" refString="Axmedov, X. A., Narbaev, Z. N., 2019. Weeds of late carrot fields. Internauka 40 (122): 26 - 27" title="Weeds of late carrot fields" volume="40" year="2019">Axmedov and Narbaev 2019</bibRefCitation>
), on tomato fields in Qibray District (
<bibRefCitation author="Axmedov, X. A." journalOrPublisher="Internauka" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="83 - 85" refId="B7454279" refString="Axmedov, X. A., Narbaev, Z. N., Arabova, N., 2020. Weeds of tomato fields. Internauka 22 (151): 83 - 85" title="Weeds of tomato fields" volume="22" year="2020">Axmedov et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
) and along margins of maize fields in Qibray District (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkamaitė, R." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Life Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7453095" refString="Plantarium Plants and lichens of Russia and neighboring countries: open online galleries and plant identification guide https://www.plantarium.ru/lang/en.html 2021-07-12T00:00:00+03:00" year="2015">Plantarium 2021</bibRefCitation>
). All recent records were misidentified as 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. angulata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="distribution in kyrgyzstan">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Distribution in Kyrgyzstan</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
Northern Tian-Shan (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F7479682" captionText="Figure 23. Distribution of Physalis philadelphica in Kyrgyzstan." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80804.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/632501" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">The species was first recorded by Georgy Lazkov in Bishkek City in 2015, as a few scattered individuals along Toktogul Street and a large population (ca. 20 flowering individuals) on the southern margin of the city. The scattered individuals withered quickly, whereas the fate of the large population was not studied. Further on, one individual was observed in flower in Sokuluk Village in 2021. The plants usually occurred in places with regular water supply, along irrigation ditches.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Open or partly shaded places on humid, fertile soils in the native distribution area; roadsides, fields, field margins, ditches and riversides, dumps and ruderal places in the secondary distribution area.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In arid areas, the species depends on the availability of water supply (
<bibRefCitation author="Buekuen, B." journalOrPublisher="Turkish Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="405 - 407" refId="B7454234" refString="Buekuen, B., Uygur, F. N., Uygur, S., Tuerkmen, N., Duesenli, A., 2002. A new record for the flora of Turkey: Physalis philadelphica Lam. var. immaculata Waterf. (Solanaceae). Turkish Journal of Botany 26: 405 - 407" title="A new record for the flora of Turkey: Physalis philadelphica Lam. var. immaculata Waterf. (Solanaceae)" volume="26" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bükün">Buekuen</normalizedToken>
et al. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Biology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
Annual or short-lived perennial (
<bibRefCitation author="Rydberg, P. A." journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Torrey Botanical Club" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="297 - 374" refId="B7453077" refString="Rydberg, P. A., 1896. The North American species of Physalis and related genera. Memoirs of the Torrey Botanical Club 4 (5): 297 - 374" title="The North American species of Physalis and related genera" volume="4" year="1896">Rydberg 1896</bibRefCitation>
), with a taproot.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
Plants of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Physalis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Physalis philadelphica" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="philadelphica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Physalis philadelphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are self-incompatible (
<bibRefCitation author="Mulato-Brito, Juan" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Fruit and Ornamental Plant Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="17 - 24" refId="B7453055" refString="Mulato-Brito, Juan, Pena-Lomeli, Aureliano, Sahagun-Castellanos, Jaime, Villanueva-Verduzco, Clemente, de Jesus Lopez-Reynoso, Jose, 2007. Self-compatibility inheritance in tomatillo (Physalis ixocarpa Brot.). Journal of Fruit and Ornamental Plant Research 67 (1): 17 - 24" title="Self-compatibility inheritance in tomatillo (Physalis ixocarpa Brot.)" volume="67" year="2007">Mulato-Brito et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). This genetic feature reduces the chances for reproduction of single plants or small colonies derived from a single source of introduction.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Physalis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Physalis ixocarpa" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ixocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Physalis ixocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sometimes separated from 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. philadelphica" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="philadelphica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. philadelphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. str., at the rank of species or subspecies (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rydberg, P. A." journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Torrey Botanical Club" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="297 - 374" refId="B7453077" refString="Rydberg, P. A., 1896. The North American species of Physalis and related genera. Memoirs of the Torrey Botanical Club 4 (5): 297 - 374" title="The North American species of Physalis and related genera" volume="4" year="1896">Rydberg 1896</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Stace, C." journalOrPublisher="Cambridge University Press" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7453030" refString="Stace, C., 2010. New Flora of the British Isles. Cambridge University Press" title="New Flora of the British Isles" year="2010">Stace 2010</bibRefCitation>
). The alleged differences are in the size of corolla (5-10 mm in diam. in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. ixocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="ixocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. ixocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 10-25 mm in diam. in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. philadelphica" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="philadelphica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. philadelphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), with corresponding differences in the size of calyx and fruit. These dimensional characters match the infraspecific variability observed in Mexico (
<bibRefCitation author="Zamora-Tavares, Pilar" journalOrPublisher="Genetic Resources and Crop Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="141 - 153" refId="B7453038" refString="Zamora-Tavares, Pilar, Vargas-Ponce, Ofelia, Sanchez-Martinez, Jose, Cabrera-Toledo, Danae, 2014. Diversity and genetic structure of the husk tomato (Physalis philadelphica Lam.) in Western Mexico. Genetic Resources and Crop Evolution 62 (1): 141 - 153" title="Diversity and genetic structure of the husk tomato (Physalis philadelphica Lam.) in Western Mexico" volume="62" year="2014">Zamora-Tavares et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), part of the native distribution area of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. philadelphica" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="philadelphica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. philadelphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, thus evidencing that the two putative taxa are synonyms. The taxonomy of this species is still unsettled, with some authors being reluctant to accept a broader concept (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pretz, Chelsea" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="170 - 192" refId="B7453122" refString="Pretz, Chelsea, Deanna, Rocio, 2020. Typifications and nomenclatural notes in Physalis (Solanaceae) from the United States. Taxon 69 (1): 170 - 192" title="Typifications and nomenclatural notes in Physalis (Solanaceae) from the United States" volume="69" year="2020">Pretz and Deanna 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
The plants observed in Kyrgyzstan were small-flowered, thus corresponding to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. ixocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" rank="species" species="ixocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">P. ixocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Physalis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Physalis philadelphica" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="philadelphica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Physalis philadelphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been an important crop in Mexico since pre-Columbian times, and now it is cultivated globally as 'tomatillo' for its edible fruits (
<bibRefCitation author="Small, E." journalOrPublisher="CRC Press" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7453047" refString="Small, E., 2011. Top 100 exotic food plants. CRC Press" title="Top 100 exotic food plants" year="2011">Small 2011</bibRefCitation>
). The long history of cultivation, as well as the presence of wild, cultivated and weedy populations already in the country of origin, may account for its high level of morphological variability (
<bibRefCitation author="Zamora-Tavares, Pilar" journalOrPublisher="Genetic Resources and Crop Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="141 - 153" refId="B7453038" refString="Zamora-Tavares, Pilar, Vargas-Ponce, Ofelia, Sanchez-Martinez, Jose, Cabrera-Toledo, Danae, 2014. Diversity and genetic structure of the husk tomato (Physalis philadelphica Lam.) in Western Mexico. Genetic Resources and Crop Evolution 62 (1): 141 - 153" title="Diversity and genetic structure of the husk tomato (Physalis philadelphica Lam.) in Western Mexico" volume="62" year="2014">Zamora-Tavares et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="introduction to kyrgyzstan">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Introduction to Kyrgyzstan</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="period of introduction">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Period of introduction</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Neophyte.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">The first record from Kyrgyzstan was dated 2015, thus falling within the period of the independence.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="pathways of introduction">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Pathways of introduction</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Transport - Contaminant: Seed contaminant.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">In Kyrgyzstan, the species is sometimes cultivated in private gardens and sold privately in marketplaces (Lazkov, pers. obs.), but its direct escape from cultivation is considered highly unlikely. Its occurrences on roadsides and waste ground in populated places suggest the arrival with contaminated grain or fodder. No further dispersal was noticed.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">In Uzbekistan, the species with certainly arrived with contaminated seed material, as indicated by its occurrence on fields. A wide variety of contaminated seed material (carrots, tomato, maize) indicates its North American origin and multiple sources of introduction.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In Russia, the species was introduced in the European part with garden seeds, as a weed of flower beds and vegetable gardens, recorded in the Middle Volga Region in the 1990s (
<bibRefCitation author="Rakov, N. S." journalOrPublisher="Izvestia Samarskogo Nauchnogo Centra Rossiiskoi Akademii Nauk" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="203 - 208" refId="B7635074" refString="Rakov, N. S., Senator, S. A., Saksonov, S. V., 2011. Antropochory in alien plants of the Middle Volga Region. Izvestia Samarskogo Nauchnogo Centra Rossiiskoi Akademii Nauk 13 (5): 203 - 208" title="Antropochory in alien plants of the Middle Volga Region" volume="13" year="2011">Rakov et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Its earliest record in Siberia (Novosibirsk, dated 1944) comes from potato fields (
<bibRefCitation author="Ebel, A. L." journalOrPublisher="Sistematicheskie zametki po materialam Gerbariya im. P. N. Krylova Tomskogo gosudarstvennogo universiteta" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="16 - 31" refId="B7635083" refString="Ebel, A. L., Zykova, E. Y., Verkhozina, A. V., Chepinoga, V. V., Kazanovsky, S. G., Mikhailova, S. I., 2015. New and rare species in adventitious flora of Southern Siberia. Sistematicheskie zametki po materialam Gerbariya im. P.N. Krylova Tomskogo gosudarstvennogo universiteta 111: 16 - 31" title="New and rare species in adventitious flora of Southern Siberia" volume="111" year="2015">Ebel et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
In the USA, the species is cultivated for fruits and frequently escapes from cultivation, becoming established along roadsides and field margins (
<bibRefCitation author="Sullivan, J. R." journalOrPublisher="Rhodora" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="305 - 326" refId="B7453086" refString="Sullivan, J. R., 2004. The genus Physalis (Solanaceae) in the southeastern United States. Rhodora 106 (928): 305 - 326" title="The genus Physalis (Solanaceae) in the southeastern United States" volume="106" year="2004">Sullivan 2004</bibRefCitation>
). In Kenya, its original introduction was intentional as a green manure crop that caused a local invasion (
<bibRefCitation author="Cunningham-van Someren, G. R." journalOrPublisher="East African Agricultural Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="29 - 33" refId="B7469466" refString="Cunningham-van Someren, G. R., 1957. The weed problem in East Africa with particular reference to cereals. East African Agricultural Journal 23 (1): 29 - 33" title="The weed problem in East Africa with particular reference to cereals" volume="23" year="1957">Cunningham-van Someren 1957</bibRefCitation>
). In the British Isles, the species originated with grain, wool and food refuse (
<bibRefCitation author="Clement, E. J." journalOrPublisher="Botanical Society of the British Isles, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7469475" refString="Clement, E. J., Foster, M. C., 1994. Alien plants of the British Isles. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London" title="Alien plants of the British Isles" year="1994">Clement and Foster 1994</bibRefCitation>
); it was also known as a contaminant of bird seed (
<bibRefCitation author="Hanson, C. G." journalOrPublisher="Watsonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="237 - 252" refId="B7469483" refString="Hanson, C. G., Mason, J. L., 1985. Bird seed aliens in Britain. Watsonia 15: 237 - 252" title="Bird seed aliens in Britain" volume="15" year="1985">Hanson and Mason 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
Further dispersal in other countries was registered as occurring with animals (
<bibRefCitation author="Cunningham-van Someren, G. R." journalOrPublisher="East African Agricultural Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="29 - 33" refId="B7469466" refString="Cunningham-van Someren, G. R., 1957. The weed problem in East Africa with particular reference to cereals. East African Agricultural Journal 23 (1): 29 - 33" title="The weed problem in East Africa with particular reference to cereals" volume="23" year="1957">Cunningham-van Someren 1957</bibRefCitation>
) and water (
<bibRefCitation author="Buekuen, B." journalOrPublisher="Turkish Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="405 - 407" refId="B7454234" refString="Buekuen, B., Uygur, F. N., Uygur, S., Tuerkmen, N., Duesenli, A., 2002. A new record for the flora of Turkey: Physalis philadelphica Lam. var. immaculata Waterf. (Solanaceae). Turkish Journal of Botany 26: 405 - 407" title="A new record for the flora of Turkey: Physalis philadelphica Lam. var. immaculata Waterf. (Solanaceae)" volume="26" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bükün">Buekuen</normalizedToken>
et al. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
). Its riverbed occurrence in Spain (
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Bellver, Carlos" journalOrPublisher="Orsis" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" pagination="167 - 189" refId="B7469492" refString="Gomez-Bellver, Carlos, Alvarez, Hilari, Saez, Llorenc, 2016. New contributions to the knowledge of the alien flora of the Barcelona province (Catalonia, Spain). Orsis 30: 167 - 189" title="New contributions to the knowledge of the alien flora of the Barcelona province (Catalonia, Spain)" volume="30" year="2016">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gómez-Bellver">Gomez-Bellver</normalizedToken>
et al. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
) seems to be connected with this type of dispersal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="source of introduction">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Source of introduction</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Presumably North America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="invasion status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Invasion status</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Casual; ephemeral or locally persisting. The species may become established in places with regular water supply; so far, no long-term survival has been observed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="evidence of impact">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Evidence of impact</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Agriculture - no impact (so far, not recorded on fields, although recent surveys are lacking). Native ecosystems - no impact (not found outside populated places). Urban areas - minor impact (casual occurrence as a ruderal plant).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" type="trend">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Trend</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">Increasing (observed).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80804">
The species has been noticed in Kyrgyzstan only recently, as a newcomer. Its regular recent occurrence as a weed or ruderal plant in Uzbekistan may suggest further spreading also in Kyrgyzstan. Its recent introduction and subsequent expansion in Turkey (
<bibRefCitation author="Economou, G." journalOrPublisher="John Wiley and Sons" pageId="0" pageNumber="80804" refId="B7454221" refString="Economou, G., Uludag, A., Kraehmer, H., 2016. Atlas of weed mapping. John Wiley and Sons" title="Atlas of weed mapping" year="2016">Economou et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
) indicates that the species is potentially invasive in regularly irrigated areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
